    {
      "id": "BYtC",
      "code_hash": "3450f59223935d41d8f87b5ce2cd3435",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"interpretation\">Interpretation</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">This reconstruction is a nearest-neighbor approximation in embedding space, not a proof of exact inversion by itself. Strong recovery at early or intermediate layers suggests that token identity remains highly recoverable from hidden states, while degradation across layers can reveal where representations become more contextual or abstract.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">The exact inversion result in the paper is stronger: it concerns injectivity of the model mapping and motivates dedicated inversion procedures such as SIPIT rather than simple nearest-neighbor lookup.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "RGSE",
      "code_hash": "e1d95e3d1118086d5700bba8fdadc0cf",
      "outputs": [],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "Kclp",
      "code_hash": "92cd3fb4df85d7f859d54ad95d3925d4",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"why-this-matters\">Why This Matters</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">If hidden states retain enough information to reconstruct the original input, then they should not be treated as harmless intermediate artifacts. This has implications for interpretability, model auditing, and privacy.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">In practical terms, systems that store or transmit hidden states may be storing information that is much closer to the original prompt than many practitioners assume.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "emfo",
      "code_hash": "7b2069df2d053c8e87681fcd2b665422",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"notes-and-limitations\">Notes and Limitations</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>This notebook uses embedding-space nearest neighbors, not the full inversion algorithm from the paper.</li>\n<li>Reconstruction quality depends heavily on the selected layer.</li>\n<li>Cosine similarity is a useful proxy for token alignment, but it is not equivalent to exact invertibility.</li>\n<li>Chat templates, tokenizer behavior, and special tokens can affect the recovered sequence.</li>\n</ul></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
